content.text: Thank You.  We are so grateful for your time.

The circle task and the letter task are about how much the background affects your
judgements of the brighness or the identity of the letter.  Your job was to focus in on
the center, and some people could better ignore the background than others.  This
is called "cognitive control."  Is cognitive control the same for all things?  Here, we 
explored whether cognitive control was the same for letter identification as it was 
for brightness judgments.  Are people who can ignore the background in one task
good at ignoring the background in the other, or is the ability to ignore specific to
the task at hand. 

If you are interested in this research, contact Professor Jeff Rouder, jrouder@uci.edu

In this task you will complete 4 blocks with 80 trials each.

In each trial, you will see a 3 by 3 letter grid:

As before, we would like to ask you to set the screen 
to full screen mode and eliminate all distractions (such as music 
and other open programs and tabs).

Next, we will provide some instructions.

Press the spacebar to continue.

Your task is to identify as fast and as accurately as possible
whether the center letter (i.e., the letter in the middle) belongs to the "A" or "H"
category. You will learn more about the two categories shortly.

This was Block ${ parameters.block } of 4.

Take a break.

Press the spacebar to continue.

For instance, in the scenario below the center letter belongs
to the "A" category. This means that the correct response in this trial would be "A".

Importantly, in each trial the center letter and the background letters will change.

However, your task is to focus solely on the center letter and ignore the 
letters surrounding it. Perform the task as fast and as accurately as possible.

Press the spacebar to continue.

If you think the center letter belongs to the "A" category, press the "A" key.
If you think the center letter belongs to the "H" category, press the "H" key.

We now start the real experiment. 

Remember: only judge the category of the center letter and try to 
ignore the neighboring letters.

Press the spacebar to continue.

This is the second task of the experiment.

This task will also take around 20-30 minutes to 
complete. You will have the opportunity to take breaks 
after each block.

Press the spacebar to continue.

The aim of the first warm-up block is to familiarize you with
the different levels of the center letter. For this reason, you will
initially only see and judge one letter, that is, the center letter.

Press the spacebar to continue.

This was the first warm-up.

Press the spacebar to continue with the next block.

Here you see all levels of the center letter at once. 

The upper four letters belong to the "H" category.

The lower four letters belong to the "A" category.

Press the spacebar to continue.

In this block, as in the real experiment, you will see a 3 by 3 letter grid.
As explained earlier, your task is to estimate whether the center letter
belongs to the "A" or "H" category.

Complete the task as fast and as accurately as possible.

Press the spacebar to continue.

This was the warm-up.

Press the spacebar to begin the real experiment.

Place your fingers on the "A" and "H" letter on the keyboard,
then spress the spacebar to begin the first warm-up block.

Place your fingers on the "A" and "H" letter on the keyboard,
then spress the spacebar to begin the second warm-up block.
